WEBVTT

00:07.520 --> 00:09.600
Now, Michael...
Michael, for your yearbook picture...

00:09.640 --> 00:11.760
don't forget to do
the over-the-shoulder shot.

00:11.840 --> 00:13.800
That's the best one.

00:15.200 --> 00:17.120
Ah, yeah.
I love that pose.

00:17.160 --> 00:19.360
It makes me look coy.

00:21.880 --> 00:25.120
Oh. Hey, guys,
Tommy Hedges just got his picture taken...

00:25.160 --> 00:27.080
with a big, old booger.

00:27.160 --> 00:31.040
So, why were you
in Tommy Hedges's picture?

00:32.439 --> 00:35.520
So, wait. He had a booger,
and you didn't tell him?

00:35.600 --> 00:39.040
He'll find out.
It'll be in the yearbook.

00:39.080 --> 00:42.120
It's true.
That's how I found out I was adorable.

00:43.160 --> 00:45.120
No, seriously.

00:45.160 --> 00:48.720
The only thing more important than your
yearbook picture is your yearbook quote.

00:48.800 --> 00:50.720
Ah, I already
got that covered.

00:50.760 --> 00:54.560
My quote's gonna be,
"What a long, strange trip it's been."

00:54.640 --> 00:57.440
Yeah, that's freakin' profound.

00:57.480 --> 00:59.800
Kelso, every lame-o hippie...

00:59.880 --> 01:02.560
in the history of time
has used that quote.

01:02.600 --> 01:05.400
Well, yeah.
That's 'cause it's good.

01:05.480 --> 01:08.280
No, Michael. Your quote
has to be meaningful...

01:08.360 --> 01:10.240
so you can remember
the good times...

01:10.320 --> 01:13.680
when you're, like, 30,
with no reason left to live.

01:13.760 --> 01:18.600
Okay, hidden in Jackie's extremely
disturbing thought is a grain of truth.

01:18.680 --> 01:20.600
We need a really
good quote this year.

01:20.680 --> 01:23.720
Well, all the best quotes
are about things that mean a lot to you.

01:23.800 --> 01:25.760
Like, for example, me.

01:25.800 --> 01:28.520
Or my hair,
or my personality...

01:28.600 --> 01:32.040
or the sparkle I bring
to your dull, gray lives.

01:32.120 --> 01:35.440
Or the feeling of relief
we get when you leave the room.

01:36.720 --> 01:39.360
No. You know what?
We need a quote about all of us.

01:39.400 --> 01:43.840
- Like, maybe like how we all met.
- Remember how we first met?

01:43.920 --> 01:47.440
Oh, is this a sexy story?

01:47.520 --> 01:51.560
- It's really more sad than sexy.
- Yeah.

01:51.640 --> 01:53.800
That's pretty much
how it goes for you, isn't it?

01:54.840 --> 01:56.760
Yeah.

02:01.760 --> 02:04.480
Okay, now, got your brownies
for the new neighbors, Eric?

02:04.520 --> 02:06.440
Yes, Mommy.

02:06.520 --> 02:08.639
How do I look?

02:08.720 --> 02:12.040
- Well, you got a little something...
- Don't touch it!

02:12.120 --> 02:15.160
I had to sleep sitting up
to keep it like this.

02:15.240 --> 02:18.360
Well, I just hope these new neighbors
are better than the last one.

02:18.440 --> 02:21.560
That Gus Griffin
was a complete dumb-ass.

02:22.520 --> 02:25.120
Hiya, neighbors!

02:25.200 --> 02:27.880
Well, hello.
We were just coming to welcome you.

02:27.960 --> 02:32.120
Looks like we beat you to the punchity-punch.

02:32.200 --> 02:34.080
Oh, damn.

02:36.360 --> 02:38.280
I'm Bob Pinciotti.

02:38.360 --> 02:41.160
This is my daughter, Donna.
My wife Midge'll be over later.

02:41.200 --> 02:43.120
Her thumb's caught
in something right now.

02:45.320 --> 02:47.680
Well, we've all done that.

02:47.720 --> 02:49.640
I guess.

02:49.720 --> 02:53.240
Well, I'm Kitty,
and this is Red...

02:53.320 --> 02:56.640
and this is our son Eric.

02:56.720 --> 02:58.920
Eric, say hello to Donna.

03:04.560 --> 03:07.440
What are you looking at,
string bean?

03:10.760 --> 03:14.280
Wow.
You're strong.

